          <div class="maintext">
           <p class="intro">
            <em>
             Berkeley in the News
            </em>
            is a daily selection of articles and commentaries in the news media that mention UC Berkeley. The views and opinions expressed in these articles do not necessarily reflect the official policies or positions of the campus.
           </p>
           <p class="bin_date">
            Tuesday, 5 March 2019
           </p>
           <p class="item">
            1.
            <span class="bin_headline">
             Questions abound after Trump threatens to strip funding from colleges that don't support free speech
            </span>
            <br>
             <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/">
              Washington Post
             </a>
             <span class="regreq">
              (*requires registration)
             </span>
             <br>
              <span class="byline">
               Susan Svrluga
              </span>
             </br>
            </br>
           </p>
           <p>
            President Trump's announcement Saturday that he would cut funding to universities that don't agree to protect free speech has been met with favor and dismay, depending on observers' viewpoints. For the second time in making such a threat, the president pointed to
            <b>
             Berkeley
            </b>
            as an example of why such a policy is required. This time, he brought to the stage the victim of a recent assault that occurred on campus, suggesting that the victim should sue the university and the state. The campus responded with a lengthy statement, informing the community and public about why the assault was not a free speech case, along with a detailed account of how the campus has handled the situation. As this article points out, the president's threat raises questions, such as: "Was this political rhetoric, or an imminent policy change? What would qualify as a commitment to free speech, and who would get to decide? And what money was in question -- research funding or tuition grants for low-income students?" Peter McPherson, president of the Associate of Public and Land-grant Universities, said in a statement: "An executive order is unnecessary as public research universities are already bound by the First Amendment, which they deeply respect and honor. ... It is core to their academic mission." Berkeley officials couldn't agree more. This article provides a brief history of Berkeley's efforts to protect free speech in recent years. For more on the recent assault case, see the latest campus statement at
            <a href="https://news.berkeley.edu/2019/03/02/statement-reaffirming-campuss-commitment-to-free-speech/">
             Berkeley News
            </a>
            . Stories on this topic have appeared in more than 1,250 sources since Saturday, including the
            <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/03/05/us/ap-us-trump-campus-free-speech.html">
             New York Times (AP)
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/trump-threatens-to-cut-federal-research-funding-over-free-speech-65558">
             The Scientist
            </a>
            ,
            <a href="https://www.chronicle.com/article/Legal-Scholars-Don-t-Know/245817?cid=wsinglestory_hp_1">
             Chronicle of Higher Education
            </a>
            , and
            <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeltnietzel/2019/03/05/trumps-free-speech-executive-order-oh-the-ironies/#7a97146627db">
             Forbes
            </a>
            .
            <br>
             <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2019/03/05/questions-abound-after-trump-threatens-strip-funding-colleges-that-dont-support-free-speech/">
              Full Story
             </a>
            </br>
           </p>
           <p class="item">
            2.
            <span class="bin_headline">
             Evidence grows that Trump's trade wars are hitting US economy
            </span>
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/">
             San Francisco Chronicle Online
            </a>
            <span class="regreq">
             (*requires registration)
            </span>
            <br/>
            <span class="byline">
             Shawn Donnan, Bloomberg
            </span>
           </p>
           <p>
            A study co-authored by
            <b>
             doctoral economics student Patrick Kennedy
            </b>
            is one of two published in the past week, suggesting that President Trump's tariffs are a risky experiment. The study, co-authored with World Bank chief economist Pinelopi Goldberg and economists from UCLA and Columbia, projects that annual losses just from the higher cost of imports would cost the U.S. economy $68.8 billion, or almost 0.4 percent of gross domestic product. It also suggests that consumers and U.S. companies would be on the hook for most of the tariffs' costs, with the key victims to date being farmers and blue-collar workers in red states. "Workers in very Republican counties bore the brunt of the costs of the trade war, in part because retaliations disproportionately targeted agricultural sectors, and in part because U.S. tariffs raised the costs of inputs used by these counties," the economists wrote.
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Evidence-grows-that-Trump-s-trade-wars-are-13664070.php">
             Full Story
            </a>
           </p>
           <p class="item">
            3.
            <span class="bin_headline">
             Demanding open access, UC breaks with world's largest scholarly research publisher
            </span>
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.mercurynews.com/">
             San Jose Mercury News
            </a>
            <span class="regreq">
             (*requires registration)
            </span>
            <br/>
            <span class="byline">
             Lisa M. Krieger
            </span>
           </p>
           <p>
            Commenting on the
            <b>
             UC system's
            </b>
            recent decision to discontinue its costly subscriptions to Elsevier's academic publications, Heather Joseph, executive director of the Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition, says: "It's a very important development. While a number of individual institutions have canceled their journal subscription with Elsevier, this is the first time an entire statewide system has done it. ... And perhaps even more importantly, the UC libraries made it clear that this decision isn't just about money. ... They're pushing for a new vision of sharing the knowledge, making sure that it's available to everyone and not just to those who can afford to pay."
            <b>
             Jeffrey MacKie-Mason, Berkeley's chief librarian and a co-chair of UC's negotiation team in the Elsevier case
            </b>
            , says: "Make no mistake: The prices of scientific journals now are so high that not a single university in the U.S. -- not the University of California, not Harvard, no institution -- can afford to subscribe to them all. ... Publishing our scholarship behind a paywall deprives people of the access to and benefits of publicly funded research. That is terrible for society." For more on this, see
            <a href="https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/press-room/uc-terminates-subscriptions-worlds-largest-scientific-publisher-push-open-access-publicly">
             UC's statement from the Office of the President
            </a>
            , a
            <a href="https://news.lib.berkeley.edu/elsevier-outcome">
             letter to Berkeley faculty from campus leaders
            </a>
            , and a
            <a href="https://news.berkeley.edu/2019/02/28/why-uc-split-with-publishing-giant-elsevier/">
             Q&amp;A on the topic
            </a>
            . Other stories have appeared in more than 300 sources since UC made its decision, including
            <a href="https://www.chemistryworld.com/news/university-of-california-terminates-contract-with-elsevier-over-journal-costs-and-open-access/3010200.article">
             Chemistry World
            </a>
            and
            <a href="https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190304/09220141728/big-win-open-access-as-university-california-cancels-all-elsevier-subscriptions-worth-11-million-year.shtml">
             Tech Dirt
            </a>
            .
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/03/04/demanding-open-access-uc-rebuffs-worlds-largest-publisher/">
             Full Story
            </a>
           </p>
           <p class="item">
            4.
            <span class="bin_headline">
             Clark killing revives push to toughen police shooting rules
            </span>
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/">
             San Francisco Chronicle Online
            </a>
            <span class="regreq">
             (*requires registration)
            </span>
            <br/>
            <span class="byline">
             Don Thompson, Associated Press
            </span>
           </p>
           <p>
            A proposed state measure that would make California the only state to restrict police officers' use of deadly force is gaining ground in the wake of the Stephon Clark killing. But some legal experts think that imposing a statewide standard might be counterproductive, since the only way to really change the trend is to have police adopt a different mindset on using force. Commenting on the measure, and referring to his book
            <i>
             When Police Kill
            </i>
            ,
            <b>
             law professor Franklin Zimring
            </b>
            says: "The key issues are not criminal prosecution standards but rules and incentives that police administration provides -- what my book calls 'don't shoot' and 'stop shooting' rules and values." The New York City Police Department has reduced fatal shootings by officers there by introducing tougher standards, training, and oversight, and Professor Zimring has praised their approach. This story appeared in more than 200 sources.
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/news/crime/article/Clark-killing-revives-push-to-toughen-police-13662727.php">
             Full Story
            </a>
           </p>
           <p class="item">
            5.
            <span class="bin_headline">
             Public Defender Jeff Adachi Mourned By Hundreds During City Hall Memorial
            </span>
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/">
             San Francisco Chronicle Online
            </a>
            <span class="regreq">
             (*requires registration)
            </span>
            <br/>
            <span class="byline">
             Bay City News Service
            </span>
           </p>
           <p>
            Hundreds of people attended a memorial for San Francisco Public Defender and
            <b>
             Berkeley alum Jeff Adachi
            </b>
            on Monday. Adachi was just 59 when he died on Feb. 22. He was an advocate of reforming the state's cash-bail system, fought alleged abuse in the city's police and sheriff's departments, and advocated for families of victims who'd been shot by police. First elected in 2002, he was California's only elected public defender. For more on this, see our story at
            <a href="https://news.berkeley.edu/2019/02/28/jeff-adachi-remembered/">
             Berkeley News
            </a>
            .
            <br/>
            <a href="https://www.sfgate.com/news/bayarea/article/Public-Defender-Jeff-Adachi-Mourned-By-Hundreds-13662532.php">
             Full Story
            </a>
           </p>
           <p>
